---
---

<div class="grid gap-10 sm:grid-cols-2 sm:gap-0">
  <!-- Without -->
  <div class="sm:border-r sm:border-border/60 sm:pr-8">
    <div class="mb-4 flex items-center gap-2">
      <span class="h-1.5 w-1.5 rounded-full bg-muted-foreground/60"></span>
      <span
        class="font-heading text-[10px] font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.25em] text-muted-foreground"
        >without a vault</span
      >
    </div>
    <p class="mb-4 text-sm leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
      Three months in. You ask the model to add a feature. It doesn't know auth
      is JWT with 15-minute expiry. It generates session-based auth. Now the
      project has two auth systems. Nobody knows why.
    </p>
    <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
      Every session starts from zero. Every decision gets re-made. The codebase
      accumulates contradictions.
    </p>
  </div>

  <!-- With -->
  <div class="sm:pl-8">
    <div class="mb-4 flex items-center gap-2">
      <span class="h-1.5 w-1.5 rounded-full bg-[color:var(--accent-amber)]"></span>
      <span
        class="font-heading text-[10px] font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.25em] text-[color:var(--accent-amber)]"
        >with a vault</span
      >
    </div>
    <p class="mb-4 text-sm leading-relaxed text-foreground">
      Same point in time. You load the implementation primitive. The model reads
      the compiled vault. It knows auth uses JWT, knows the API contract, knows
      optimistic locking was chosen because write volume is low.
    </p>
    <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed text-foreground">
      It implements the feature within those constraints. Every line traces to a
      decision. New sessions aren't blank slates — they're continuations.
    </p>
  </div>
</div>
